{"cursor":"9862","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"'Thomas' (and Tomas) is a common surname used by the British (primarily Welsh),\nFrench, German, Dutch, Danish, and South Indian (Nasrani).\n\nIt derives from the medieval personal name, of Biblical origin, from Aramaic\nt'om'a, a byname meaning 'twin'. It was borne by one of the disciples of Christ,\nbest known for his skepticism about Christ's resurrection (). The th- spelling\nin English results from the initial letter of the name in the Greek New\nTestament being a theta. The English pronunciation as t rather than a dental\nfricative is the result of French influence from an early date. In Britain, the\nsurname is widely distributed throughout the country, but especially common in\nWales and Cornwall. Thomas is the ninth most common surname in the United\nKingdom. [http://www.britishsurnames.co.uk/surnames/THOMAS British\nsurnames] It is found as a personal name among Christians in India, and in\nthe United States; it is also used as a family name among the Jewish Christian\n(Nasrani) families from Kerala, South India.\n\nIn the 1990 United States Census, Thomas was the twelfth most common surname,\naccounting for 0.3% of the population. United States Census Bureau (9 May\n1995). . Retrieved on 4 July 2008.\n\nIn France, Thomas (pronounced ) is the third most widespread surname after\nMartin and Bernard, with over 100,000 people with this name. [http://www.notrefamille.com/v2/services-nom-de-\nfamille/nom.asp?nom=thomas&x=0&y=0&rubrique=&page= Repartition and frequency of\nsurname Thomas in France]\n","linknr":282,"url":"Thomas_(surname)","recorded":1362569993,"links":14,"instances":["disambiguation","disambiguation","disambiguation","name","disambiguation","disambiguation","disambiguation","rugby_union","disambiguation","disambiguation","disambiguation","disambiguation","disambiguation","disambiguation","disambiguation","disambiguation","disambiguation","author","disambiguation","disambiguation